          k
          )
        
        =
        (
        n
        +
        1
        )
        
          H
          
            n
          
        
        −
        n
        
        ,
      
    
    {\displaystyle s_{n}=\sum _{k=1}^{n}{{\frac {1}{k}}(n+1-k)}=(n+1)H_{n}-n\,,}
  which can also be written as

  
    
      
        
          ∑
          
            k
            =
            1
          
          
            n
          
        
        
          
            H
            
              k
            
          
        
        =
        (
        n
        +
        1
        )
        (
        
          H
          
            n
            +
            1
          
        
        −
        1
        )
        
        .
      
    
    {\displaystyle \sum _{k=1}^{n}{H_{k}}=(n+1)(H_{n+1}-1)\,.}
  


==== Example 2: Modified binomial coefficient sums and the binomial transform ====
As another example of using generating functions to relate sequences and manipulate sums, for an arbitrary sequence 
  
    
      
        ⟨
        
          f
          
            n
          
        
        ⟩
      
    
    {\displaystyle \langle f_{n}\rangle }
   we define the two sequences of sums

  
    
      
        
          s
          
            n
          
        
        :=
        
          ∑
          
            m
            =
            0
          
          
            n
          
        
        
          
            
              (
            
            
              n
